1
00:00:15,599 --> 00:00:17,693
[GRUNTS THEN SIGHING]

2
00:00:27,236 --> 00:00:29,238
[SIGHS]

3
00:00:35,410 --> 00:00:37,629
Don't worry about that, all right?

4
00:00:37,829 --> 00:00:40,332
Look down. Look at the grass.

5
00:00:40,541 --> 00:00:42,543
[CHUCK SIGHING]

6
00:00:42,876 --> 00:00:45,049
Kick off your shoes like this.

7
00:00:55,264 --> 00:00:57,733
- When was the last time you did that?
-Heh.

8
00:00:57,933 --> 00:01:00,027
Feels good, right?

9
00:01:01,186 --> 00:01:02,563
Yeah.

10
00:01:02,771 --> 00:01:05,194
Grass between your toes.

11
00:01:06,191 --> 00:01:08,364
Feels nice.

12
00:01:08,569 --> 00:01:10,321
- Yeah.
-Yeah.

13
00:01:12,364 --> 00:01:13,616
<i>Hm.</i>

14
00:01:15,867 --> 00:01:19,417
Well, I think maybe--
Maybe it's time we go in.

15
00:01:19,621 --> 00:01:21,339
We have a lot of work to do.

16
00:01:21,540 --> 00:01:24,419
We need to get ready.
You need to get ready.

17
00:01:24,626 --> 00:01:27,971
If I were Schweikart and Cokely,
I'd seek a restraining order.

18
00:01:29,006 --> 00:01:30,599
Turn this into a civil harassment issue.

19
00:01:30,799 --> 00:01:34,019
Ah, Schweikart and Cokely can come
after me with a restraining order...

20
00:01:34,219 --> 00:01:36,563
...or anything else they got, I'll be ready.

21
00:01:36,763 --> 00:01:38,640
Confidence is good.

22
00:01:38,849 --> 00:01:41,523
Facts on your side, better.

23
00:01:41,977 --> 00:01:44,230
Know what you're walking into.

24
00:01:45,272 --> 00:01:47,366
[INHALES DEEPLY]

25
00:01:48,025 --> 00:01:49,197
[GRUNTS]

26
00:01:57,618 --> 00:01:59,040
[SIGHS]

27
00:02:01,371 --> 00:02:02,964
[CHUCKLES]

28
00:02:03,915 --> 00:02:05,758
CHUCK: House needs a coat of paint.
-Yeah.

29
00:02:05,959 --> 00:02:07,961
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

30
00:02:09,671 --> 00:02:12,720
[My]

31
00:02:26,271 --> 00:02:27,318
[GIGGLING]

32
00:02:27,522 --> 00:02:29,365
MIKE:
I got her all her shots.

33
00:02:29,566 --> 00:02:32,160
Healthy gums. And no worms. No fleas.

34
00:02:32,361 --> 00:02:33,408
I promise you...

35
00:02:33,612 --> 00:02:37,162
...if the little sucker has fleas,
I'll kick her butt myself.

36
00:02:37,366 --> 00:02:40,461
Yeah, it's just a dog...

37
00:02:40,661 --> 00:02:42,880
Hey, it's good to have a dog around.

38
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:47,130
Bad guys think twice about
breaking into a house with a dog.

39
00:02:47,334 --> 00:02:50,304
STACEY: Yeah, I bet that one's gonna
keep a lot of burglars away.

40
00:02:50,504 --> 00:02:52,723
It's just a thought.

41
00:02:54,091 --> 00:02:57,311
You know, you can always
keep her over at my place.

42
00:02:57,511 --> 00:03:00,060
Kaylee can visit her
any time she wants.

43
00:03:03,183 --> 00:03:04,856
Well, if you decide to keep her...

44
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:07,859
...I got a giant bag of puppy chow
out in the car for you.

45
00:03:08,063 --> 00:03:11,033
All the supplies.
Everything you need.

46
00:03:14,861 --> 00:03:15,908
[SIGHS]

47
00:03:16,113 --> 00:03:17,911
All right.

48
00:03:18,323 --> 00:03:20,075
- Aw. . ..
-What's that?

49
00:03:21,368 --> 00:03:23,541
The dog can stay here.

50
00:03:23,745 --> 00:03:25,247
You sure?

51
00:03:25,455 --> 00:03:27,128
Yes.

52
00:03:27,332 --> 00:03:28,959
Thank you.

53
00:03:29,626 --> 00:03:32,049
All right. Done.

54
00:03:32,379 --> 00:03:33,972
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

55
00:03:34,339 --> 00:03:36,433
Excuse me a minute.

56
00:03:42,055 --> 00:03:43,557
Yeah?

57
00:03:46,685 --> 00:03:48,312
Sure.

58
00:03:51,148 --> 00:03:52,695
Yup.

59
00:03:55,861 --> 00:03:57,488
Got it.

60
00:04:04,870 --> 00:04:06,918
Is everything okay?

61
00:04:07,122 --> 00:04:10,547
Yeah. Just a lead on a job opportunity.

62
00:04:11,918 --> 00:04:15,047
Your Honour, Mr. Schweikart
and his cohorts are attempting...

63
00:04:15,255 --> 00:04:17,633
...to keep me away from their victims.
-Victims?

64
00:04:17,841 --> 00:04:20,094
My clients. Yes.
You're denying me access.

65
00:04:20,302 --> 00:04:22,851
Even the worst prisoners
in this building...

66
00:04:23,054 --> 00:04:24,931
...are allowed access to a lawyer.

67
00:04:25,140 --> 00:04:27,108
Are you saying my poor, elderly clients...

68
00:04:27,309 --> 00:04:29,232
...have fewer rights than jail inmates?

69
00:04:29,436 --> 00:04:32,610
Not at all. And no one is denying
Mr. McGill access to his clients.

70
00:04:32,814 --> 00:04:35,237
- We're denying access to the property.
-It's semantics.

71
00:04:35,442 --> 00:04:38,241
Within Sandpiper Crossing's rights.
The building's private property.

72
00:04:38,445 --> 00:04:41,665
- Paid for by the residents.
-But managed by licensed professionals.

73
00:04:41,865 --> 00:04:43,788
Okay. One at a time, gentlemen.

74
00:04:43,992 --> 00:04:48,418
Mr. Schweikart, you're denying him
access on what grounds?

75
00:04:48,622 --> 00:04:52,092
These assisted living residents
have a daily routine that they're used to.

76
00:04:52,292 --> 00:04:57,344
Mr. McGill, who is loud and flamboyant,
is a disturbance to these routines.

77
00:04:57,547 --> 00:05:00,346
Residents who want to see a lawyer,
free to leave whenever they want.

78
00:05:00,550 --> 00:05:01,722
Leave whenever they want?

79
00:05:01,927 --> 00:05:05,147
We're talking about elderly
and infirm people here.

80
00:05:05,347 --> 00:05:09,693
The most common phrase in this place?
"I've fallen and I can't get up."

81
00:05:09,893 --> 00:05:12,897
There's phone consultations.
There's mail and messenger services.

82
00:05:13,104 --> 00:05:14,947
Plenty of ways to confer with clients.

83
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:18,948
But for residents who don't want to be
afflicted with Mr. McGill's presence...

84
00:05:19,152 --> 00:05:20,745
...this becomes an
issue of civil harassment.

85
00:05:20,946 --> 00:05:23,995
Wow, you are stretching
that definition to its limit.

86
00:05:24,199 --> 00:05:26,543
And FYI, old people adore me.

87
00:05:26,743 --> 00:05:27,960
Okay. I've heard enough.

88
00:05:28,161 --> 00:05:30,914
I have enough here to let me rule
on this restraining order.

89
00:05:33,375 --> 00:05:36,424
Yeah. Ha-ha-ha. Don't worry, Chuck.

90
00:05:36,628 --> 00:05:39,347
That's not smoke you smell.
That's me. Heh, heh.

91
00:05:39,548 --> 00:05:45,931
This mo-fo is on fire. Your baby bro
kicked some Schweikart ass today.

92
00:05:46,429 --> 00:05:48,477
What the hell's all this?

93
00:05:48,682 --> 00:05:52,812
There was a delivery
while you were in court.

94
00:05:53,478 --> 00:05:55,480
Schweikart and Cokely sent this?
What is it?

95
00:05:55,689 --> 00:05:58,863
The served interrogatories
on each class representative.

96
00:05:59,067 --> 00:06:01,616
This box is deposition notices.

97
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:06,701
Documents calling into question
the mental health of our elderly clients.

98
00:06:06,908 --> 00:06:09,377
Attempting to stop the class
from being certified...

99
00:06:09,578 --> 00:06:11,421
...on the grounds
they're not competent.

100
00:06:11,788 --> 00:06:13,836
Oh, this is just the beginning.

101
00:06:14,124 --> 00:06:16,126
They're gonna continue
this document dump...

102
00:06:16,334 --> 00:06:18,052
...until we're drowning in paperwork.

103
00:06:18,253 --> 00:06:23,384
All right. We can deal with this.
I mean, hey.

104
00:06:23,592 --> 00:06:27,938
It's, uh--
it's just paperwork. Right?

105
00:06:28,138 --> 00:06:31,517
- It's no big deal. Just hit it head on.
-Jimmy.

106
00:06:31,725 --> 00:06:34,353
Prioritise.
The most important stuff first.

107
00:06:34,561 --> 00:06:37,861
Or is it better to deal with the easy stuff?

108
00:06:38,064 --> 00:06:40,658
You know, get that off the decks.

109
00:06:40,859 --> 00:06:44,534
You tell me, Chuck. You just
point to a box. We can do this.

110
00:06:44,738 --> 00:06:47,207
- Jimmy, we need to talk.
-Chuck.

111
00:06:47,407 --> 00:06:50,206
- Sit down, won't you?
-No, I'm good.

112
00:06:50,410 --> 00:06:52,833
I know you're not gonna like
what I have to say next.

113
00:06:53,038 --> 00:06:54,540
But facts are facts.

114
00:06:54,748 --> 00:06:57,092
And what we're facing here...

115
00:06:57,292 --> 00:07:00,796
A case this size, it is not
a two man job. We need help.

116
00:07:01,004 --> 00:07:03,302
- No.
-And for the good of the clients...

117
00:07:03,506 --> 00:07:05,600
...we need to refer this case--
-Don't say it.

118
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:07,552
Refer it out to HHM.

119
00:07:07,761 --> 00:07:11,231
Damn it, Chuck. No. Come on.

120
00:07:11,431 --> 00:07:16,278
We can do this.
We're doing great on our own.

121
00:07:16,478 --> 00:07:20,233
We don't need Hamlin
or anyone else. I mean, hey.

122
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:23,535
We can Erin Brockovich
the shit out of this case.

123
00:07:23,735 --> 00:07:25,954
Erin Brockovich didn't do it alone.

124
00:07:26,154 --> 00:07:28,248
She and Ed Masry
brought in heavy hitters...

125
00:07:28,448 --> 00:07:30,997
...from Los Angeles to get that case
across the goal line.

126
00:07:31,201 --> 00:07:35,001
And that's what we need to do.
And there's no shame in that.

127
00:07:35,205 --> 00:07:36,673
This is our case.

128
00:07:36,873 --> 00:07:40,468
Yes, it's ours.
And the task ahead is monumental.

129
00:07:40,669 --> 00:07:42,967
Could we do it alone?

130
00:07:43,672 --> 00:07:47,051
Could two men alone build
the Brooklyn Bridge? Maybe.

131
00:07:47,258 --> 00:07:49,477
But it would take forever.

132
00:07:49,678 --> 00:07:53,308
Just how long do you think the
residents of Sandpiper Crossing have?

133
00:07:54,182 --> 00:07:59,530
Referring this case to HHM
is for the good of the clients.

134
00:07:59,729 --> 00:08:03,108
That argument you won today
against the restraining order...

135
00:08:03,316 --> 00:08:05,239
...the judge was never
gonna grant that.

136
00:08:05,443 --> 00:08:07,741
Schweikart is throwing softballs.

137
00:08:07,946 --> 00:08:10,244
And he's gonna keep on
throwing them over and over.

138
00:08:10,448 --> 00:08:11,825
We'll be busy swatting them away...

139
00:08:12,033 --> 00:08:14,081
...we'll never spend time
on the actual case.

140
00:08:14,285 --> 00:08:16,788
This case will span years.

141
00:08:16,997 --> 00:08:20,376
And we don't have the capital
to carry it forward by ourselves.

142
00:08:20,583 --> 00:08:21,960
We simply don't.

143
00:08:22,168 --> 00:08:24,170
[SIGHS THEN SCOFFS]

144
00:08:33,304 --> 00:08:35,932
- Fine.
-So?

145
00:08:36,641 --> 00:08:38,393
The case goes to HHM?

146
00:08:40,186 --> 00:08:43,907
Hail Satan. I submit to the dark side.

147
00:08:45,442 --> 00:08:47,911
I'll call Kim and arrange a meeting.

148
00:08:48,111 --> 00:08:51,490
All right. Good, Jimmy.
Thank you.

149
00:08:51,698 --> 00:08:54,668
I know you'll come to see
that it's for the best.

150
00:08:59,122 --> 00:09:00,590
[CHUCKLES]

151
00:09:01,583 --> 00:09:03,085
[SIGHS]

152
00:09:07,047 --> 00:09:11,177
I guess I'll have to get
an office right next to yours.

153
00:09:13,011 --> 00:09:15,890
Finally out of the mailroom, huh?

154
00:10:39,514 --> 00:10:41,516
[LINE RINGING]

155
00:10:41,724 --> 00:10:42,976
[GRUNTING]

156
00:10:47,272 --> 00:10:48,990
Yes. Hello.

157
00:10:49,941 --> 00:10:52,785
No. It's me.

158
00:10:56,739 --> 00:10:58,992
[SIREN WAILING AND
CAR HORNS HONKING IN DISTANCE]

159
00:11:05,165 --> 00:11:07,167
[DOOR OPENS]

160
00:11:27,645 --> 00:11:31,070
- This the place where we wait?
-Think so.

161
00:12:02,889 --> 00:12:04,482
80...

162
00:12:08,102 --> 00:12:10,651
What'd our guy tell you about the job?

163
00:12:12,815 --> 00:12:14,692
Not much.

164
00:12:16,486 --> 00:12:18,454
It's a protection job. Civilian.

165
00:12:19,864 --> 00:12:21,741
Guy is as green as they come...

166
00:12:21,950 --> 00:12:25,250
...but we'll be in there
to make sure things fly right.

167
00:12:28,957 --> 00:12:32,427
You been doing this long?
I just assume we're all heavy hitters.

168
00:12:32,627 --> 00:12:35,346
And it makes sense.
The vet recommends the best of the best.

169
00:12:35,546 --> 00:12:39,926
Dealing with some of these ethnic types,
blood tends to run a little hotter.

170
00:12:40,134 --> 00:12:43,559
That's just science. Physiology.

171
00:12:43,763 --> 00:12:47,438
There's historical precedent.
Know what I'm saying?

172
00:12:49,018 --> 00:12:51,942
So, what you packing?

173
00:12:53,273 --> 00:12:56,322
- A pimento.
-Sorry, what?

174
00:12:56,526 --> 00:12:58,699
Pimento sandwich.

175
00:12:58,903 --> 00:12:59,950
[CHUCKLES]

176
00:13:00,154 --> 00:13:03,328
That's funny. Pimento.

177
00:13:05,118 --> 00:13:06,745
No, I mean, what are you carrying?

178
00:13:06,953 --> 00:13:09,126
You know, the piece?
What's the make?

179
00:13:09,330 --> 00:13:14,052
Pimento is a cheese.
They call it the caviar of the south.

180
00:13:14,252 --> 00:13:16,471
You don't want to tell me
what you're carrying, so be it.

181
00:13:16,671 --> 00:13:19,220
But you don't have to
be a douche about it.

182
00:13:19,424 --> 00:13:21,927
Just told you what I'm carrying.

183
00:13:24,345 --> 00:13:27,098
So you're saying
you don't have a gun?

184
00:13:27,307 --> 00:13:28,934
Is that what you're saying?

185
00:13:29,142 --> 00:13:31,611
How are you here without a gun?

186
00:13:31,811 --> 00:13:34,280
- You have a gun?
-Yeah.

187
00:13:34,480 --> 00:13:37,484
Yeah. Of course.
He's got a gun.

188
00:13:37,942 --> 00:13:40,445
I got at least two guns on me
that I'll tell you about.

189
00:13:40,653 --> 00:13:43,156
I go old school with
a Wilson Combat 1911.

190
00:13:43,364 --> 00:13:45,037
I got a Glock 22 Gen 3.

191
00:13:45,241 --> 00:13:47,209
And those are just the ones
I'll tell you about.

192
00:13:47,410 --> 00:13:48,627
Mm.

193
00:13:49,537 --> 00:13:52,757
I mean, what the hell? Really?

194
00:13:52,957 --> 00:13:55,255
How do you not pack a gun?

195
00:14:05,553 --> 00:14:07,555
[CAR DOOR OPENS]

196
00:14:12,727 --> 00:14:16,106
Hi. Hello. Uh, my name is Price.

197
00:14:16,689 --> 00:14:19,112
Um, actually,
that's not my name.

198
00:14:19,317 --> 00:14:23,914
But, uh, I have a nephew named Price.
I've always kind of liked that name.

199
00:14:24,113 --> 00:14:26,081
Anyway, we're not
dealing with names today.

200
00:14:26,282 --> 00:14:29,206
You can tell me or not tell me yours.
Or a fake one is fine.

201
00:14:29,535 --> 00:14:34,257
Um, if I need to talk to you, I'd prefer
something other than "Hey, you."

202
00:14:34,457 --> 00:14:38,132
Um, either way, you all come highly
recommended, so thank you.

203
00:14:38,336 --> 00:14:41,385
First order of business,
we have a long drive ahead of us.

204
00:14:41,589 --> 00:14:44,468
Uh, I have a cooler of water
in the car, some soft drinks.

205
00:14:44,675 --> 00:14:48,475
I don't drink coffee,
but there is a diner on the corner.

206
00:14:48,679 --> 00:14:53,480
Also a bathroom in there in case
you need to go before, uh, we go.

207
00:14:53,684 --> 00:14:55,732
Second order. Uh, money.

208
00:14:55,937 --> 00:15:02,365
Just to be clear that the agreed upon fee
of $500 per man is...

209
00:15:02,568 --> 00:15:03,740
...agreed upon.

210
00:15:03,945 --> 00:15:05,788
- If that's acceptable--
-Yeah, I have a thought.

211
00:15:06,697 --> 00:15:07,744
Yeah.

212
00:15:07,949 --> 00:15:11,123
How about you give me
and Man Mountain 750 each?

213
00:15:11,327 --> 00:15:14,627
And send Uncle Fester there home.
He's not carrying a gun.

214
00:15:14,831 --> 00:15:16,208
He's useless.

215
00:15:17,125 --> 00:15:20,971
- Is that true? You didn't bring a gun?
-I didn't think I'd need one.

216
00:15:21,170 --> 00:15:23,093
[CHUCKLES]

217
00:15:23,297 --> 00:15:24,344
It's a protection job.

218
00:15:24,549 --> 00:15:25,766
It's basic common sense...

219
00:15:25,967 --> 00:15:28,516
...that you need a gun
to protect your employer. Duh.

220
00:15:28,719 --> 00:15:29,936
You're dead weight.

221
00:15:30,138 --> 00:15:32,891
- He's just a third wheel without a piece.
-I'll tell you what.

222
00:15:33,099 --> 00:15:35,443
If I need a gun, I'll use one of his.

223
00:15:35,643 --> 00:15:37,190
Really? One of my guns?

224
00:15:37,395 --> 00:15:39,397
How do you picture
that happening exactly?

225
00:15:39,605 --> 00:15:41,448
Well, I guess I'm gonna
take it from you.

226
00:15:41,649 --> 00:15:45,779
That-- That is just special. Huh?

227
00:15:45,987 --> 00:15:48,957
Take. How are you gonna
take one of my guns?

228
00:15:49,157 --> 00:15:51,831
Come on, Billy Jackoff.

229
00:15:52,368 --> 00:15:54,496
Take my gun from me.

230
00:15:54,704 --> 00:15:56,251
Let me see it.

231
00:15:56,456 --> 00:16:00,051
Here. I'll make it easy for you.

232
00:16:05,173 --> 00:16:07,551
You can make it not so easy.

233
00:16:07,758 --> 00:16:09,681
Sure thing.

234
00:16:11,345 --> 00:16:12,767
You got it.

235
00:16:15,600 --> 00:16:17,853
What the--? Son of a-- Unh!

236
00:16:18,728 --> 00:16:20,321
[GASPING AND COUGHING]

237
00:16:21,272 --> 00:16:24,867
Okay. Let's see what you got.

238
00:16:26,903 --> 00:16:30,908
Yeah. Yeah. Yeah. A guy like you...

239
00:16:31,115 --> 00:16:34,585
I'll bet you'd have an ankle holster,
wouldn't you?

240
00:16:34,785 --> 00:16:38,380
You know, that's cute. What else?

241
00:16:38,581 --> 00:16:40,629
[GRUNTING AND COUGHING]

242
00:16:44,003 --> 00:16:47,928
Wow, now, that's impressive.

243
00:16:48,132 --> 00:16:51,227
So many guns,
I don't know which one to use.

244
00:16:51,427 --> 00:16:55,102
How about you? You want one?

245
00:17:01,979 --> 00:17:03,231
All right.

246
00:17:03,439 --> 00:17:05,862
[DOOR OPENS]

247
00:17:16,494 --> 00:17:17,746
Let's go.

248
00:17:17,954 --> 00:17:22,676
- But we need three guys.
-No. No, we don't. Come on. Let's go.

249
00:17:31,217 --> 00:17:33,436
Oh, he'll be fine.

250
00:17:33,636 --> 00:17:39,439
And now that I'm doing the job alone,
I get the full 1500. We agree upon that?

251
00:17:39,642 --> 00:17:40,985
Sure.

252
00:17:41,185 --> 00:17:43,779
[MAN CONTINUES
GASPING AND GRUNTING]

253
00:17:45,106 --> 00:17:47,108
[SIGHS]

254
00:17:51,070 --> 00:17:52,868
JIMMY:
You got this, okay? No problem.

255
00:17:53,406 --> 00:17:54,453
Yes.

256
00:17:54,657 --> 00:17:57,706
- The suit okay? Is it too tight or too hot?
-Yeah.

257
00:17:57,910 --> 00:18:00,413
No, I mean. No. No. It's good.

258
00:18:00,621 --> 00:18:02,464
Well, you look good. Oh--

259
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:06,469
Can't even tell
that's under there.

260
00:18:06,669 --> 00:18:08,262
It was a good idea.

261
00:18:08,462 --> 00:18:12,092
Yeah. At any point, it's too much,
you're uncomfortable...

262
00:18:12,300 --> 00:18:15,645
...we'll turn around and come home.
You want maybe, like, a safe word?

263
00:18:15,845 --> 00:18:18,098
How about, "Get me the hell home"?

264
00:18:18,306 --> 00:18:20,525
That'll work. Okay.

265
00:18:20,725 --> 00:18:22,568
Let's do this.

266
00:18:22,768 --> 00:18:24,611
Let's do this.

267
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:29,033
JIMMY:
Okay.

268
00:18:29,942 --> 00:18:31,615
Looking good.

269
00:18:31,819 --> 00:18:35,323
We're just going
for a little ride.

270
00:18:37,241 --> 00:18:39,790
Here. Let me get that for you.

271
00:18:40,828 --> 00:18:42,546
Here you go.

272
00:18:50,087 --> 00:18:51,134
[SIGHS]

273
00:18:51,339 --> 00:18:54,138
CHUCK: Jimmy.
-Just a sec.

274
00:18:58,554 --> 00:19:01,103
- Oh, crap.
-What is it?

275
00:19:01,307 --> 00:19:03,935
I must have left my stupid phone
on last night. It's dead.

276
00:19:04,143 --> 00:19:05,770
Well, could you put it
in the trunk?

277
00:19:05,978 --> 00:19:07,980
Oh. Yeah.

278
00:19:14,487 --> 00:19:16,489
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

279
00:19:21,243 --> 00:19:23,962
Okay. Thanks.

280
00:19:24,997 --> 00:19:26,624
That everyone?

281
00:19:27,083 --> 00:19:28,676
They'll be here in one minute.

282
00:19:28,876 --> 00:19:32,050
Anyone still have a phone,
add it to the collection now.

283
00:19:32,755 --> 00:19:35,474
- Okay. Shut it down.
-Okay. Got it.

284
00:19:40,971 --> 00:19:42,314
[BEEPING]

285
00:20:08,791 --> 00:20:10,759
- How you doing? You doing all right?
-Yeah.

286
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:12,962
Okay. Great stuff.

287
00:20:14,130 --> 00:20:15,928
[JIMMY GRUNTING]

288
00:20:23,431 --> 00:20:24,603
Okay. We're walking.

289
00:20:25,683 --> 00:20:27,185
Walking in, Chuck.

290
00:20:27,393 --> 00:20:28,440
[CHUCK SIGHING]

291
00:20:28,644 --> 00:20:30,317
Here we go.

292
00:20:54,378 --> 00:20:57,473
- Good to see you. Welcome home.
-Howard, you didn't need to do all this.

293
00:20:57,673 --> 00:20:59,926
Oh, I couldn't have stopped them
if I wanted to. Heh, heh.

294
00:21:00,134 --> 00:21:01,977
- Come on, let's get you upstairs.
-Yeah. Sure.

295
00:21:02,178 --> 00:21:04,897
Francis. Brenda. Jose, you shaved.

296
00:21:16,233 --> 00:21:21,285
To date, we have 68 very willing plaintiffs
signed to the class-action...

297
00:21:21,489 --> 00:21:25,619
...with hopes of raising that number
to 350 or more.

298
00:21:25,826 --> 00:21:29,626
Many more, now that we know Sandpiper
has facilities in five states.

299
00:21:29,830 --> 00:21:34,381
Fraud, unfair and deceptive
trade practises, and racketeering.

300
00:21:34,585 --> 00:21:36,838
Jesus. Heh, heh. Guys, this is...

301
00:21:38,255 --> 00:21:41,350
Well, no case is ever a slam dunk.

302
00:21:41,550 --> 00:21:43,018
But I feel <i>as</i> confident about this...

303
00:21:43,219 --> 00:21:44,971
...as anything that's
come through our doors.

304
00:21:45,179 --> 00:21:47,307
Francis, start putting together teams
to travel out of state.

305
00:21:47,515 --> 00:21:48,562
Talk to these residents.

306
00:21:48,766 --> 00:21:51,986
Pair fourths with our best second years.
Laura will take care of the travel.

307
00:21:52,186 --> 00:21:54,780
Kim, Daniel. Take the list
of clients Jimmy's signed.

308
00:21:54,980 --> 00:21:58,701
Introduce yourself as the face of HHM.
Make them feel secure and confident.

309
00:21:58,901 --> 00:22:01,199
Hey, Howard.
I'm glad you're all excited.

310
00:22:01,403 --> 00:22:04,031
But can we slow down a second
and discuss terms, maybe?

311
00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:05,537
Oh, of course.

312
00:22:05,741 --> 00:22:07,288
Kind of shot out of a cannon
with this case.

313
00:22:07,493 --> 00:22:10,042
- It's exciting stuff you have here.
-I get it.

314
00:22:10,246 --> 00:22:12,214
Look, Chuck is already
an equity partner.

315
00:22:12,414 --> 00:22:14,837
You, as the lawyer who
brought this case to the firm...

316
00:22:15,042 --> 00:22:17,511
...we could guarantee you,
say, 2O percent...

317
00:22:17,711 --> 00:22:20,885
...of the common fund share
of the final settlement.

318
00:22:21,090 --> 00:22:23,138
That will work.

319
00:22:23,342 --> 00:22:27,643
That's a few years down the road.
As for money for you now, uh...

320
00:22:27,847 --> 00:22:30,100
...we don't do referral fees.
Chuck will agree.

321
00:22:30,307 --> 00:22:32,935
- HHM doesn't view that as ethical.
-As we discussed.

322
00:22:33,143 --> 00:22:36,272
But what we could do
is arrange an of-counsel fee...

323
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:40,701
...for the time that you've already put in.
Time that you spent building the case.

324
00:22:40,901 --> 00:22:42,824
I think we could go as high as 20,000.

325
00:22:43,654 --> 00:22:46,749
- That, too, will work.
-Great.

326
00:22:47,992 --> 00:22:50,495
Give us an invoice.
I'll have Helen cut you a cheque.

327
00:22:50,703 --> 00:22:55,504
Oh, got it right here.
And I'd like to use 312 as an office.

328
00:22:55,708 --> 00:22:59,008
- It's right next to Chuck's.
-I'm sorry?

329
00:22:59,211 --> 00:23:03,512
Three-twelve. I know, it's got that view
that clients love, but you know what?

330
00:23:03,716 --> 00:23:08,313
That's a waste of space. The waiting area
by the kitchen is just as good.

331
00:23:09,513 --> 00:23:10,810
Um...

332
00:23:11,015 --> 00:23:14,110
Well, come on, guys.
I mean, I need an office.

333
00:23:16,478 --> 00:23:20,233
Can I have the room?
Everybody, please. Just give us a few.

334
00:23:24,612 --> 00:23:27,616
- Um, Howard--
-When the room's clear, Chuck.

335
00:23:37,041 --> 00:23:40,511
Jimmy. Jimmy,
I'm just gonna say it.

336
00:23:40,711 --> 00:23:43,806
- You're not working here.
-What are you talking about?

337
00:23:44,006 --> 00:23:46,350
- You said this case is a slam dunk.
-Yes.

338
00:23:46,550 --> 00:23:49,770
We want the case.
We don't want, um...

339
00:23:50,471 --> 00:23:51,848
Uh...

340
00:23:52,056 --> 00:23:55,151
The case is all we want.

341
00:23:56,268 --> 00:23:57,315
[SCOFFS]

342
00:23:57,519 --> 00:23:59,362
You gotta be...

343
00:24:00,397 --> 00:24:01,694
You're serious?

344
00:24:02,358 --> 00:24:06,238
I walk in here with a
multi-million dollar class-action lawsuit...

345
00:24:06,445 --> 00:24:10,245
...on a damn platinum platter.

346
00:24:10,699 --> 00:24:14,829
A case that I found,
that I made happen.

347
00:24:15,037 --> 00:24:18,416
And you don't want me?
Why in Christ not?

348
00:24:19,875 --> 00:24:22,594
Well, I know that you hate me, Howard.

349
00:24:22,836 --> 00:24:25,635
You better believe,
feeling goes both ways.

350
00:24:25,839 --> 00:24:29,469
But I'm willing to set that aside
to work with you on this.

351
00:24:29,677 --> 00:24:31,554
Why can't you
do the same for me?

352
00:24:31,762 --> 00:24:35,312
What is it that
you can't let go of? Huh?

353
00:24:35,516 --> 00:24:40,773
What slight did I make to your fine,
upstanding character you can't forgive?

354
00:24:40,980 --> 00:24:44,200
A majority decision has been made
by myself and the partners.

355
00:24:44,400 --> 00:24:45,652
All due respect to you, Chuck...

356
00:24:45,859 --> 00:24:48,487
...we are not taking in any
new associates into the firm.

357
00:24:48,696 --> 00:24:50,698
Bullshit! New associates?

358
00:24:50,906 --> 00:24:55,286
Someone walks in with a case like this,
you beg them to be partner.

359
00:24:55,494 --> 00:24:57,292
Tell me why.

360
00:24:57,496 --> 00:24:59,749
You didn't want me then. Okay.

361
00:24:59,957 --> 00:25:01,049
You don't want me now?

362
00:25:01,250 --> 00:25:02,923
Explain it.

363
00:25:04,670 --> 00:25:05,796
Howard.

364
00:25:07,715 --> 00:25:09,763
I don't know what to say.

365
00:25:10,342 --> 00:25:14,267
I am very disappointed.
I really think you should reconsider.

366
00:25:14,471 --> 00:25:19,147
I'm sorry, but no. I think it's best
if Jimmy takes the of-counsel fee.

367
00:25:19,351 --> 00:25:21,069
We could probably up it a bit.
Keep in mind.

368
00:25:21,270 --> 00:25:22,567
You will be well-compensated
in the back end.

369
00:25:22,771 --> 00:25:24,364
It's easy money, Jimmy.

370
00:25:24,565 --> 00:25:26,033
No reason not to take it.

371
00:25:27,109 --> 00:25:29,737
Go to hell, Howard.

372
00:25:29,945 --> 00:25:31,947
I'm not giving you my case.

373
00:25:32,322 --> 00:25:34,791
And I'm gonna tell
every one of those clients...

374
00:25:34,992 --> 00:25:38,462
...what a lying miserable
pig fucker you are.

375
00:25:39,621 --> 00:25:44,718
I will burn the whole thing to
the ground before I give it to you.

376
00:25:46,962 --> 00:25:50,717
Okay, then,
if that's your decision.

377
00:25:52,092 --> 00:25:54,390
Good luck to you moving forward.

378
00:26:00,100 --> 00:26:01,147
Oh...

379
00:26:01,351 --> 00:26:03,069
[DOOR OPENS THEN CLOSES]

380
00:26:04,188 --> 00:26:06,407
What the hell just happened?

381
00:26:09,526 --> 00:26:10,869
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

382
00:26:11,070 --> 00:26:12,242
Yeah. Come.

383
00:26:13,947 --> 00:26:15,369
Hi.

384
00:26:15,574 --> 00:26:18,828
Was wondering if you had a moment?

385
00:26:19,828 --> 00:26:22,206
Sure. Just give me a second.

386
00:26:35,344 --> 00:26:39,190
- What's up?
-I wanted to talk about what happened.

387
00:26:39,681 --> 00:26:42,184
With Sandpiper Crossing,
things didn't work out.

388
00:26:42,392 --> 00:26:45,396
It was unfortunate.
it was a good case.

389
00:26:45,729 --> 00:26:48,733
- But things happen.
-I'm just trying to understand why.

390
00:26:48,941 --> 00:26:51,364
Jimmy found that case.
He built it.

391
00:26:51,568 --> 00:26:54,071
Did all of the leg work.

392
00:26:54,279 --> 00:26:56,327
The class-action
doesn't exist without him.

393
00:26:56,532 --> 00:26:58,079
He deserves a seat at the table.

394
00:26:58,283 --> 00:26:59,910
I understand.

395
00:27:00,119 --> 00:27:04,465
But the decision
has been made, Kim.

396
00:27:04,998 --> 00:27:07,046
Thank you for your input.

397
00:27:12,381 --> 00:27:14,930
But why?

398
00:27:18,303 --> 00:27:23,901
The partners have made a decision
and the why is not your concern.

399
00:27:24,101 --> 00:27:26,354
I think it is my concern.

400
00:27:26,562 --> 00:27:28,485
And why is that?

401
00:27:30,524 --> 00:27:32,652
Because he's my friend.

402
00:27:33,443 --> 00:27:36,162
And the way I see it,
you're not treating him fairly.

403
00:27:36,655 --> 00:27:38,578
The way you see it?

404
00:27:38,782 --> 00:27:43,879
I don't know what image
you have of him, past or present...

405
00:27:44,079 --> 00:27:49,381
...or whatever he did or said to you,
but Jimmy is a good lawyer.

406
00:27:49,585 --> 00:27:51,212
And he works very hard.

407
00:27:51,628 --> 00:27:54,598
Did your friend send you
in here to say that?

408
00:27:55,966 --> 00:27:57,468
No.

409
00:27:57,968 --> 00:28:00,391
I'm saying it because I believe it.

410
00:28:02,389 --> 00:28:03,811
Well...

411
00:28:04,016 --> 00:28:05,268
...duly noted.

412
00:28:06,018 --> 00:28:07,895
Want to know what I believe?

413
00:28:08,103 --> 00:28:12,199
I believe that you're
way out of your depth in this matter.

414
00:28:12,399 --> 00:28:14,822
So the next time
that you want to come in here...

415
00:28:15,027 --> 00:28:16,745
...and tell me what I'm doing wrong...

416
00:28:16,945 --> 00:28:19,744
...you are welcome to
keep it to yourself.

417
00:28:19,948 --> 00:28:22,076
Because I don't care.

418
00:28:33,629 --> 00:28:35,131
Stop.

419
00:28:39,509 --> 00:28:41,182
Close the door.

420
00:28:51,939 --> 00:28:53,612
They're late.

421
00:28:53,941 --> 00:28:55,989
Must be traffic.

422
00:28:59,780 --> 00:29:01,953
I wonder how this is
supposed to work.

423
00:29:02,991 --> 00:29:07,417
I mean, who goes first?
Do I hand over the pills first'?

424
00:29:07,621 --> 00:29:11,797
Or do they give me the money
and then I hand over the pills?

425
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,049
I mean, I guess it makes sense
if we just exchanged...

426
00:29:15,254 --> 00:29:18,804
...at the same time, right?
I mean, that's fair.

427
00:29:19,341 --> 00:29:22,185
Maybe we just count to three.

428
00:29:22,386 --> 00:29:25,105
Probably the less talk, the better.

429
00:29:25,305 --> 00:29:26,352
Right.

430
00:29:26,556 --> 00:29:31,153
Yeah. I suppose you could
really overthink something like this.

431
00:29:31,353 --> 00:29:32,525
Yeah.

432
00:29:32,729 --> 00:29:35,858
- Well, in any case--
-Here is what is going to happen.

433
00:29:36,066 --> 00:29:38,865
You're gonna take the money.
You're going to count it.

434
00:29:39,069 --> 00:29:42,164
If it's all there,
you hand them the pills.

435
00:29:42,364 --> 00:29:44,366
Easy peasy.

436
00:29:58,714 --> 00:30:02,764
I knew we needed three guys.
I knew it. It's a three-man job.

437
00:30:03,468 --> 00:30:04,890
God.

438
00:30:22,070 --> 00:30:24,869
Hello. Hi.

439
00:30:27,200 --> 00:30:29,919
- Do you have it?
-I do.

440
00:30:32,289 --> 00:30:34,166
Do you have the money?

441
00:31:06,865 --> 00:31:08,208
Is it all there?

442
00:31:09,785 --> 00:31:11,002
Um...

443
00:31:11,953 --> 00:31:15,799
We're short 20. Twenty dollars.

444
00:31:16,458 --> 00:31:18,210
That's fine.

445
00:31:19,711 --> 00:31:23,090
Agreed amount or no deal.

446
00:31:24,383 --> 00:31:25,600
You serious?

447
00:31:26,051 --> 00:31:28,679
You saying
I intentionally shorted you?

448
00:31:28,887 --> 00:31:32,232
No. Mistakes happen.

449
00:31:33,141 --> 00:31:35,485
You really willing to blow up
this deal over 20 bucks?

450
00:31:36,728 --> 00:31:38,526
Are you?

451
00:32:04,423 --> 00:32:08,394
It's all there. Eighty milligram pills,
still factory sealed.

452
00:32:51,761 --> 00:32:53,604
You can pay me now.

453
00:32:53,805 --> 00:32:55,057
Huh?

454
00:32:55,557 --> 00:32:56,809
Oh.

455
00:33:02,689 --> 00:33:04,111
[SIGHS]

456
00:33:07,652 --> 00:33:10,496
- How did you know?
-Huh?

457
00:33:10,739 --> 00:33:13,663
How did you know not to bring a gun?

458
00:33:13,867 --> 00:33:17,917
This 1500, I'll just say
you're getting a bargain.

459
00:33:18,121 --> 00:33:20,965
I put in a lot of leg work
before coming here.

460
00:33:21,166 --> 00:33:24,966
Now, that fella you just met with,
name is Ignacio Varga.

461
00:33:25,170 --> 00:33:27,844
He runs with a
connected crew of drug dealers.

462
00:33:28,048 --> 00:33:30,767
This deal he's doing with you,
he's doing outside his crew.

463
00:33:30,967 --> 00:33:32,560
He doesn't want his bosses to know.

464
00:33:32,761 --> 00:33:36,811
So it was in his best interest
that things go very smoothly.

465
00:33:37,474 --> 00:33:39,476
- Wow.
-Mm.

466
00:33:40,310 --> 00:33:43,189
The lesson is, if you're gonna be
a criminal, do your homework.

467
00:33:43,396 --> 00:33:45,569
Wait. I'm not a bad guy.

468
00:33:45,774 --> 00:33:48,618
I didn't say you were a bad guy.
I said you're a criminal.

469
00:33:50,070 --> 00:33:51,788
What's the difference?

470
00:33:51,988 --> 00:33:55,959
I've known good criminals and bad cops.
Bad priests. Honourable thieves.

471
00:33:56,159 --> 00:33:59,959
You can be on one side
of the law or the other.

472
00:34:00,163 --> 00:34:04,293
But if you make a deal with
somebody, you keep your word.

473
00:34:04,501 --> 00:34:09,223
You can go home today with
your money and never do this again.

474
00:34:09,422 --> 00:34:12,050
But you took something
that wasn't yours.

475
00:34:12,259 --> 00:34:14,512
And you sold it for a profit.

476
00:34:14,719 --> 00:34:19,646
You're now a criminal.
Good one, bad one? That's up to you.

477
00:34:21,977 --> 00:34:24,150
I can get more pills.

478
00:34:24,563 --> 00:34:28,193
And I am sure that fella
will keep buying.

479
00:34:30,902 --> 00:34:35,453
Why don't you get us home?
You can sleep on it before you decide.

480
00:35:19,075 --> 00:35:21,703
- H9Y-
-|-ley-

481
00:35:21,911 --> 00:35:23,504
I was worried about you.

482
00:35:23,705 --> 00:35:27,676
- I must have called a dozen times.
-Sorry. My phone died.

483
00:35:27,876 --> 00:35:29,628
It's one of the perks
of living in Chuckland.

484
00:35:29,836 --> 00:35:30,883
Nowhere to plug in.

485
00:35:31,504 --> 00:35:34,428
But tonight, it's Jimmyland.

486
00:35:34,633 --> 00:35:38,354
I've got gin. I've got tequila.
I've got good Kentucky bourbon.

487
00:35:38,553 --> 00:35:39,725
And you may partake with me...

488
00:35:39,929 --> 00:35:42,352
...in any beverage of your choice
on one condition.

489
00:35:42,557 --> 00:35:44,059
You have to listen to me rant...

490
00:35:44,267 --> 00:35:46,861
...about what an unwashed asshole
your boss is.

491
00:35:47,062 --> 00:35:49,406
- Jimmy--
-No. It's true.

